======================================================================
EIGENVALUE FORMULA
======================================================================

Since sigma_P is an eigenvector of J, what is the eigenvalue?

J sigma_P = lambda * sigma_P  where lambda = sigma_P^T J sigma_P / ||sigma_P||^2.

For sigma_P in {+1,-1}^m: ||sigma_P||^2 = m.

So lambda = (1/m) * sum_{i,j} J[i,j] * chi(i+1) * chi(j+1)
          = (1/m) * sum_{i<j} 2 * J[i,j] * chi(i+1) * chi(j+1)

Now J[i,j] = hat{H}({i,j}), the pairwise interaction coefficient.

From the Walsh expansion:
  hat{H}({i,j}) = (1/2^m) * sum_{sigma} H(sigma) * sigma_i * sigma_j

So:
  lambda = (2/m) * sum_{i<j} (1/2^m) sum_sigma H(sigma) sigma_i sigma_j * chi(i+1) chi(j+1)
         = (2/m) * (1/2^m) * sum_sigma H(sigma) * [sum_{i<j} chi(i+1) chi(j+1) sigma_i sigma_j]

The inner sum sum_{i<j} chi(i+1) chi(j+1) sigma_i sigma_j
= (1/2)[(sum_i chi(i+1) sigma_i)^2 - sum_i chi(i+1)^2 sigma_i^2]
= (1/2)[(sum_i chi(i+1) sigma_i)^2 - m]  (since chi^2 = 1 and sigma^2 = 1)

Defining the "QR alignment" A(sigma) = sum_{i=1}^m chi(i) * sigma_i:
  lambda = (2/m) * (1/2^m) * sum_sigma H(sigma) * (1/2)[A(sigma)^2 - m]
         = (1/m) * (1/2^m) * sum_sigma H(sigma) * [A(sigma)^2 - m]
         = (1/m) * [E[H * A^2] - m * E[H]]

where E denotes average over {+1,-1}^m.


p=7:
